# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-durango
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-durango/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] An **all-wheel drive vehicle** (**AWD vehicle**) is one with a powertrain capable of providing power to all its wheels, whether full-time or on-demand.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] Reflects one axle with one wheel capable of being powered.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] Reflects two axles with one wheel on each capable of being powered.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] Reflects two axles with both wheels on each capable of being powered.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] Reflects three axles with both wheels on each capable of being powered.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] Reflects four axles with both wheels on each capable of being powered.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] The wheels are driven, but not dependent on a central mechanical power coupling.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] In the context of hybrid and electric vehicles, the North American designation of 'all-wheel-drive' may differ.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] In some hybrid vehicles, the combustion engine is only mechanically connected to the front wheels, while the rear wheels are powered independently by an electric motor; this may be marketed as *eAWD*.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] Furthermore, many electric vehicles have individual, unconnected motors powering each axle, or even each individual wheel, also without any center differential.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] When tire grip is good during road driving, a differential is used between the axles to avoid driveline windup.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] This is not required off-road, as the limited grip allows the tires to slip.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] All-wheel drive vehicles designed for extensive off-road use may not have such a differential, and so they suffer from wind-up when used on-road.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] Selectable 4WD also avoids this problem and requires only a simple dog clutch in the transfer case, rather than a differential.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] For this reason, most early off-road vehicles used that system; e.g., Jeep, Land Rover.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] As vehicles became more sophisticated and tires gave better winter performance in the 1960s, there was an interest in giving the benefits of all-wheel drive to conventional cars: not for off-road use but for winter use in snow and ice or on wet roads.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] Exotic vehicles such as the high-powered Jensen FF followed by the AMC Eagle, Subaru Leone and Audi Quattro series were the first to offer all-wheel drive in a high-speed road-based car.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] These, particularly the Quattro, would extensively develop this drivetrain with the use of viscous couplings and differentials to provide a safe and drivable car.
[src:dodge-durango/all-wheel-drive] The first off-road / on-road hybrids such as the Range Rover also chose the permanent all-wheel-drive system rather than manual selection.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] In geometry and other fields, **asymmetry** is an absence or violation of symmetry in an object or process, such that some transformation (such as reflection in space) results in an observable difference.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Symmetry is an important property of both physical and abstract systems and it may be displayed in precise terms or in more aesthetic terms.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] The absence of or violation of symmetry that are either expected or desired can have important consequences for a system.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Due to how cells divide in organisms, asymmetry in organisms is fairly usual in at least one dimension, with biological symmetry also being common in at least one dimension.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Louis Pasteur proposed that biological molecules are asymmetric because the cosmic [i.e. physical] forces that preside over their formation are themselves asymmetric.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] While at his time, and even now, the symmetry of physical processes are highlighted, it is known that there are fundamental physical asymmetries, starting with time.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Nature also provides several examples of handedness in traits that are usually symmetric.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Since birth defects and injuries are likely to indicate poor health of the organism, defects resulting in asymmetry often put an animal at a disadvantage when it comes to finding a mate.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] For example, a greater degree of facial symmetry is seen as more attractive in humans, especially in the context of mate selection.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] In general, there is a correlation between symmetry and fitness-related traits such as growth rate, fecundity and survivability for many species.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] This means that, through sexual selection, individuals with greater symmetry (and therefore fitness) tend to be preferred as mates, as they are more likely to produce healthy offspring.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Pre-modern architectural styles tended to place an emphasis on symmetry, except where extreme site conditions or historical developments lead away from this classical ideal.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] To the contrary, modernist and postmodern architects became much more free to use asymmetry as a design element.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] In fire-resistance rated wall assemblies, used in passive fire protection, including, but not limited to, high-voltage transformer fire barriers, asymmetry is a crucial aspect of design.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] When designing a facility, it is not always certain, that in the event of fire, which *side* a fire may come from.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Therefore, many building codes and fire test standards outline, that a symmetrical assembly, need only be tested from one side, because both sides are the same.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] However, as soon as an assembly is asymmetrical, both sides must be tested and the test report is required to state the results for each side.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] In practical use, the lowest result achieved is the one that turns up in certification listings.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Neither the test sponsor, nor the laboratory can go by an opinion or deduction as to which side was in more peril as a result of contemplated testing and then test only one side.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Both must be tested in order to be compliant with test standards and building codes.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] In mathematics, asymmetry can arise in various ways.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Examples include asymmetric relations, asymmetry of shapes in geometry, asymmetric graphs et cetera.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] In geometry, a figure is asymmetric if it does not have any reflectional, rotational, or translational symmetry (eg. a scalene triangle, where all sides and angles differ).
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] When determining whether an object is asymmetrical, look for lines of symmetry.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] For instance, a square has four lines of symmetry, while a circle has infinite.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] If a shape has no lines of symmetry, then it is asymmetrical, but if an object has any lines of symmetry, it is symmetrical.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] An asymmetric relation is a binary relation R defined on a set of elements such that if $aRb$ holds for elements a and b , then $bRa$ must be false.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Stated differently, an asymmetric relation is characterized by a necessary absence of symmetry of the relation in the opposite direction.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Inequalities exemplify asymmetric relations.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] If a is less than b ( $a<b$ ), then a cannot be greater than b ( $a\ngtr b$ ).
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] This highlights how the relations "less than", and similarly "greater than", are not symmetric.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] In contrast, if a is equal to b ( $a=b$ ), then b is also equal to a ( $b=a$ ).
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Thus the binary relation "equal to" is a symmetric one.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] In general an Asymmetric tensor is defined by the change of signs $(-/+)$ of its solution under the interchange of two indexes.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] The Epsilon-tensor is an example of an asymmetric tensor.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] For even or uneven permutations of the indexes the tensor is either 1 or -1.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Certain molecules are chiral; that is, they cannot be superposed upon their mirror image.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Chemically identical molecules with different chirality are called *enantiomers*; this difference in orientation can lead to different properties in the way they react with biological systems.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Asymmetry arises in physics in a number of different realms.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] The original non-statistical formulation of thermodynamics was asymmetrical in time: it claimed that the entropy in a closed system can only increase with time.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] This was derived from the Second Law (any of the two, Clausius' or Lord Kelvin's statement can be used since they are equivalent) and using the Clausius' Theorem (see Kerson Huang ISBN 978-0471815181).
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] The later theory of statistical mechanics, however, is symmetric in time.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Although it states that a system significantly below maximum entropy is very likely to evolve *towards* higher entropy, it also states that such a system is very likely to have evolved *from* higher entropy.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Symmetry is one of the most powerful tools in particle physics, because it has become evident that practically all laws of nature originate in symmetries.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Violations of symmetry therefore present theoretical and experimental puzzles that lead to a deeper understanding of nature.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Asymmetries in experimental measurements also provide powerful handles that are often relatively free from background or systematic uncertainties.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Until the 1950s, it was believed that fundamental physics was left-right symmetric; i.e., that interactions were invariant under parity.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Although parity is conserved in electromagnetism, strong interactions and gravity, it turns out to be violated in weak interactions.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] The Standard Model incorporates parity violation by expressing the weak interaction as a chiral gauge interaction.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Only the left-handed components of particles and right-handed components of antiparticles participate in weak interactions in the Standard Model.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] A consequence of parity violation in particle physics is that neutrinos have only been observed as left-handed particles (and antineutrinos as right-handed particles).
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Hudson found a clear violation of parity conservation in the beta decay of cobalt-60.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Weinrich modified an existing cyclotron experiment and immediately verified parity violation.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] After the discovery of the violation of parity in 1956–57, it was believed that the combined symmetry of parity (P) and simultaneous charge conjugation (C), called *CP*, was preserved.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] For example, CP transforms a left-handed neutrino into a right-handed antineutrino.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] In 1964, however, James Cronin and Val Fitch provided clear evidence that CP symmetry was also violated in an experiment with neutral kaons.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] CP violation is one of the necessary conditions for the generation of a baryon asymmetry in the early universe.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Combining the CP symmetry with simultaneous time reversal (T) produces a combined symmetry called CPT symmetry.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] CPT symmetry must be preserved in any Lorentz invariant local quantum field theory with a Hermitian Hamiltonian.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] As of 2006, no violations of CPT symmetry have been observed.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] The baryons (i.e., the protons and neutrons and the atoms that they comprise) observed so far in the universe are overwhelmingly matter as opposed to anti-matter.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] This asymmetry is called the baryon asymmetry of the universe.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Isospin is the symmetry transformation of the weak interactions.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] This symmetry arises at a more fundamental level as a symmetry between up-type and down-type quarks.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Isospin symmetry in the strong interactions can be considered as a subset of a larger flavor symmetry group, in which the strong interactions are invariant under interchange of different types of quarks.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Including the strange quark in this scheme gives rise to the Eightfold Way scheme for classifying mesons and baryons.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Isospin is violated by the fact that the masses of the up and down quarks are different, as well as by their different electric charges.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Because this violation is only a small effect in most processes that involve the strong interactions, isospin symmetry remains a useful calculational tool, and its violation introduces corrections to the isospin-symmetric results.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] Because the weak interactions violate parity, collider processes that can involve the weak interactions typically exhibit asymmetries in the distributions of the final-state particles.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] These asymmetries are typically sensitive to the *difference* in the interaction between particles and antiparticles, or between left-handed and right-handed particles.
[src:dodge-durango/asymmetrical] They can thus be used as a sensitive measurement of differences in interaction strength and/or to distinguish a small asymmetric signal from a large but symmetric background.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Auburn Hills is notable as the home of Oakland University, and the site of the North American headquarters of Stellantis.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The city is a major hub of manufacturing and commerce, particularly in the automotive industry, with facilities of more than 50 automotive corporations.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Before incorporating as a city in 1983, the area was part of the now-defunct Pontiac Township.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] In 1821, Auburn Hills began as Pontiac Township which included the village of Auburn at what is today the corner of Auburn and Squirrel roads.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Situated on the Clinton River, it was named by Aaron Webster, the first settler, for Auburn, New York.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] His sawmill and grist mill attracted settlers to Auburn.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] After the streets were laid out in 1826, Auburn rivaled nearby Pontiac until the 1860s, when it lost its own prosperity.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The town was renamed Amy in 1880, and it officially became Auburn Heights in 1919.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Pontiac Township bordered the city of Pontiac on two sides.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] In 1908, automobile pioneer John Dodge bought a farmhouse 3 miles (4.8 km) northeast of Auburn Heights to use as his country retreat.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] He and his wife, Matilda Dodge Wilson, continued to buy farmland, eventually totaling 1,400 acres.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Dodge died in 1920, and Matilda Dodge later married lumber baron Alfred Gaston Wilson, with whom she built one of America's castles, Meadow Brook Hall, on a portion of the estate in present day Rochester Hills at a cost of $4 million ($56.6 million in 2024).
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] In 1957, Matilda Dodge Wilson donated her land to Michigan State University, leading to the creation of Oakland University.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] John Dodge's oldest child, Winifred Dodge, married real estate baron Wesson Seyburn, who built his own country retreat 2.5 miles (4.0 km) north of Auburn Heights.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The estate included hunting land, dog kennels, a swimming pool, horse stables, and a 5,000-square-foot (460 m2) Colonial Revival house.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Pontiac Township purchased the estate in 1975, and adapted the buildings for government use.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Today, it is known as the Auburn Hills Civic Center.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The first recorded use of the name "Auburn Hills," in 1964, was by Oakland Community College.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] They named their campus (a former Nike missile base) at Featherstone and Squirrel roads for the town of Auburn and the hilly terrain in the area.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The township attempted to incorporate as Pontiac Heights in 1971, but was denied by state officials.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Pontiac Township became a charter township in 1978, to protect itself from further annexation.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] In 1983, Pontiac Township merged with the village of Auburn Heights to become the City of Auburn Hills.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] It is not to be confused with the similarly named city of Auburn, Michigan, that exists in Bay County, near Saginaw Bay.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 16.64 square miles (43.10 km2), of which 16.60 square miles (42.99 km2) is land and 0.04 square miles (0.10 km2) (0.24%) is water.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] As of the 2020 census, Auburn Hills had a population of 24,360.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] 14.4% of residents were under the age of 18 and 13.9% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] For every 100 females there were 95.8 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 95.4 males age 18 and over.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] There were 10,253 households in Auburn Hills, of which 20.3% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Of all households, 35.2% were married-couple households, 26.9% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 30.6% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] About 37.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 10.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] There were 11,032 housing units, of which 7.1% were vacant.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.0% and the rental vacancy rate was 6.5%.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] As of the census of 2010, there were 21,412 people, 8,844 households, and 4,923 families living in the city.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The population density was 1,289.9 inhabitants per square mile (498.0/km2).
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] There were 9,965 housing units at an average density of 600.3 per square mile (231.8/km2).
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The racial makeup of the city was 66.3% White, 18.5% African American, 0.3% Native American, 8.9% Asian, 2.7% from other races, and 3.4% from two or more races.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 7.8% of the population.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] There were 8,844 households, of which 27.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 38.8% were married couples living together, 12.4% had a female householder with no husband present, 4.5% had a male householder with no wife present, and 44.3% were non-families.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] 33.5% of all households were made up of individuals, and 7.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The average household size was 2.24 and the average family size was 2.90.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The median age in the city was 31.4 years.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] 19.4% of residents were under the age of 18; 17.8% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 31.9% were from 25 to 44; 21.6% were from 45 to 64; and 9.4% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The gender makeup of the city was 48.4% female and 51.6% male.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] As of the census of 2000, there were 19,837 people, 8,064 households, and 4,604 families living in the city.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The population density was 1,194.5 inhabitants per square mile (461.2/km2).
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] There were 8,822 housing units at an average density of 531.2 per square mile (205.1/km2).
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The racial makeup of the city was 75.92% White, 13.22% African American, 0.32% Native American, 6.33% Asian, 0.04% Pacific Islander, 1.56% from other races, and 2.61% from two or more races.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 4.50% of the population.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] There were 8,064 households, out of which 26.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them; 43.0% were married couples living together; 10.5% had a female householder with no husband present and 42.9% were non-families.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] 33.1% of all households were made up of individuals, and 6.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The average household size was 2.25 and the average family size was 2.92.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] For every 100 females, there were 98.3 males.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 97.5 males.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The median income for a household in the city was $51,376, and the median income for a family was $60,849.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Males had a median income of $45,686 versus $34,015 for females.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The per capita income for the city was $25,529.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] About 3.9% of families and 6.3% of the population were below the poverty line, including 6.4% of those under age 18 and 4.4% of those age 66 or over.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Auburn Hills roughly follows the course of Interstate 75 and is home to a prosperous business community.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] In the early 1980s, Oakland University partnered with developers to create a technology and research park.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The Oakland Technology Park was approved by the city in 1985, with Comerica, EDS, and Chrysler to build campuses there.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The city's many tech and office buildings host 80,000 people during the workday.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Great Lakes Crossing Outlets, an enclosed super-regional outlet shopping mall, opened November 12, 1998.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] In 2002, the area at Auburn and Squirrel was revitalized as the "Village Center" with streetscape improvements.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Pedestrian-friendly development is encouraged in this district now known simply as Downtown Auburn Hills.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] In 2017, Maserati announced it was moving its U.S. headquarters from Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey to the former Walter P.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] School districts serving sections of Auburn Hills include Avondale School District, Pontiac School District, and Rochester Community Schools.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The Avondale School District operates two elementary schools in the city limits: R.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Grant Graham Elementary School and Auburn Elementary School.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Portions of Auburn Hills in ASD are zoned to these schools.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] All ASD residents are zoned to Avondale Middle School in Rochester Hills and Avondale High School in Auburn Hills.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Other ASD facilities in Auburn Hills include the district administrative offices and Avondale Montessori.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] A Pontiac school district school, Will Rogers Elementary School, is located in northeastern Auburn Hills.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The main campus of Oakland University sits within Auburn Hills.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Oakland Community College is also situated in Auburn Hills.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Auburn Hills is home to several local parks, many of which are open year-round.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] A skateboard, inline skate and BMX bike park open to all ages and skill levels.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The use of the facility is always free and it remains open from April to November, 8 a.m. until dusk.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Popular hiking and walking attraction with numerous nature trails.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] A fishing pond and picnic area are also available for public use.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The park offers open lawn areas and a picnic shelter with a fireplace inside.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The park features a softball field, 9-hole disc golf course, tennis courts, two play structures, and swings.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] An expansive, 16-mile (26 km) walkway through the heart of Oakland County.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The trail cuts through several different cities, including Rochester, Rochester Hills, Sylvan Lake, Auburn Hills, and Pontiac.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The 2.1-mile (3.4 km) section of trail within Auburn Hills is covered in finely crushed stone, ideal for walking, jogging and biking.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Featuring a fireman-themed "tot-lot" for children ages 2–5, Dennis Dearing Jr.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Memorial Park is a popular spot for families with children.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The park also has swings, picnic tables and open space areas for picnic or play.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] A two-acre park which contains a play structure, sand volleyball courts, a paved play area and open space for activities.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Located adjacent to downtown Auburn Hills and along the Clinton River, Riverside Park is a popular spot during the warmer months.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] A canoe launch is open during the warm season.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Located near downtown Auburn Hills, this park has picnic areas, both open and sheltered, standing barbecue grills and heated restrooms which remain open year-round.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] Visitors can navigate through the park on a paved pathway system, which includes a bridge over the Clinton River.
[src:dodge-durango/auburn-hills-michigan] The park also contains four basketball courts and play structures.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:dodge-durango/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The **powertrain layout** of a motorised vehicle such as a car is often defined by the location of the engine or motors and the drive wheels.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] Layouts can roughly be divided into three categories: front-wheel drive (FWD), rear-wheel drive (RWD) and four-wheel drive (4WD).
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] Many different combinations of engine location and driven wheels are found in practice, and the location of each is dependent on the application for which the vehicle will be used.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The *front-engine, front-wheel-drive* layout (abbreviated as FF layout) places both the internal combustion engine and driven wheels at the front of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] This is the most common layout for cars since the late 20th century.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] Some early front-wheel drive cars from the 1930s had the engine located in the middle of the car.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] A rear-engine, front-wheel-drive layout is one in which the engine is between or behind the rear wheels, and drives the front wheels via a driveshaft, the complete reverse of a conventional front-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicle layout.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] This layout has only been used on prototype and concept cars.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The *front-engine, rear-wheel drive* layout (abbreviated as FR layout) is one where the engine is located at the front of the vehicle and driven wheels are located at the rear.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] This was the traditional automobile layout for most of the 20th century, and remains the most common layout for rear-wheel drive vehicles.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The *mid-engine, rear-wheel drive* layout (abbreviated as MR layout) is one where the rear wheels are driven by an engine placed just in front of them, behind the passenger compartment.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] In contrast to the rear-engined RR layout, the centre of mass of the engine is in front of the rear axle.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] This layout is typically chosen for its low moment of inertia and relatively favorable weight distribution.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The *rear-engine, rear-wheel drive* layout (abbreviated as RR layout) places both the engine and drive wheels at the rear of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The centre of mass of the engine is between the rear axle and the rear bumper, in contrast to the MR layout.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] Although common in electric cars, and in transit buses and coaches due to the elimination of the drive shaft with low-floor bus, this layout has become increasingly rare in internal combustion engine passenger cars.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The Porsche 911 is notable for its continuous use of the RR layout since 1963.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] Drivetrains where power can be sent to all four wheels are referred to as either four-wheel drive (4WD) or all-wheel drive (AWD).
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The *front-engine, four-wheel drive* layout (abbreviated as F4 layout) places the engine at the front of the vehicle and drives all four roadwheels.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] This layout is typically chosen for better control on many surfaces, and is an important part of rally racing as well as off-road driving.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] Most four-wheel-drive layouts are front-engined and are derivatives of earlier front-engine, rear-wheel-drive designs.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The *mid-engine, four-wheel drive* layout (abbreviated as M4 layout) places the engine in the middle of the vehicle, between both axles and drives all four road wheels.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] Although the term "mid-engine" can mean the engine is placed anywhere in the vehicle such that the centre of gravity of the engine lies between the front and rear axles, it is usually used for sports cars and racing cars where the engine is behind the passenger compartment.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The motive output is then sent down a shaft to a differential in the centre of the car, which in the case of an M4 layout, distributes power to both front and rear axles.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The *rear-engine, four-wheel drive* layout (abbreviated as R4) places the engine at the rear of the vehicle, and drives all four wheels.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] This layout is typically chosen to improve the traction or the handling of existing vehicle designs using the rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout (RR).
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] For example, the Porsche 911 added all-wheel drive to the existing line-up of rear-wheel drive models in 1989.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] In automotive design, dual-motor, four-wheel-drive layout is mainly used by battery electric vehicles by having two electric motors that each drives the front and rear axle, creating a four-wheel drive layout.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] This is made possible by the smaller size of electric motors compared to internal combustion engines (ICEs), which in addition are also accompanied by a bulky engine cooling system, allowing it to be fit more versatilely into multiple locations.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The use of separate motors for the front and rear drive wheels eliminates the need of a drive shaft that is ubiquitous in four-wheel drive ICE vehicles.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] This frees up space for bigger battery modules, which are commonly mounted on the chassis floor between the axles.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The dual-motor layout is beneficial in re-distributing torque and power to maximize effective propulsion in response to road grip conditions and weight transfer in the vehicle.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] For example, during hard acceleration, the front motor must reduce torque and power in order to prevent the front wheels from overspinning as weight transfers to the rear of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The excess power is transferred to the rear motor where it can be used immediately.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The opposite applies when braking, when the front motor can accept more regenerative braking torque and power.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] However dual-motor vehicles usually have less range for the same battery size than single-motor designs.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] In addition, electric vehicles may be equipped with more than two electric motors to achieve greater power output and superior handling.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] The first mass-produced triple-motor layout was introduced on the Audi e-tron in 2020, which consists of one motor at the front and two motors at the rear.
[src:dodge-durango/automobile-layout] A rare example of a non-electric vehicle utilizing this layout is the Citroën 2CV Sahara, which has two flat-twin petrol engines.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The functional design and development of a modern motor vehicle is typically done by a large team from many different disciplines also included within automotive engineering, however, design roles are not associated with requirements for professional- or chartered-engineer qualifications.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Automotive design in this context focuses primarily on developing the visual appearance or aesthetics of vehicles, while also becoming involved in the creation of product concepts.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Automotive design as a professional vocation is practiced by designers who may have an art background and a degree in industrial design or in transportation design.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] For the terminology used in the field, see the glossary of automotive design.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The task of the design team is usually split into three main aspects: exterior design, interior design, and color and trim design.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Graphic design is also an aspect of automotive design; this is generally shared amongst the design team as the lead designer sees fit.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The design focuses not only on the isolated outer shape of automobile parts, but concentrates on the combination of form and function, starting from the vehicle package.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The aesthetic value will need to correspond to ergonomic functionality and utility features as well.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Though not all the new vehicular gadgets are to be designated as factory standard items, some of them may be integral to determining the future course of any specific vehicular models.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The design team(s) responsible for the exterior of the vehicle develops the proportions, shape, and surface details of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Exterior design is first done by a series of manual sketches and digital drawings.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Progressively, more detailed drawings are executed and approved by appropriate layers of management, followed by digital rendering to images.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Consumer feedback is generally sought at this point to help iteratively refine vehicle concepts according to the targeted market and will continue throughout the rest of the design refinement process.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] After more progressive refinement, industrial plasticine and or digital models are developed from and along with the drawings and images.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The data from these models are then used to create quarter-scale and finally full-sized mock-ups of the final design.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] With three- and five-axis CNC milling machines, the clay model is first designed in a computer program and then "carved" using the machine and large amounts of clay.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Even in times of photorealistic (three-dimensional) software and virtual models on power walls, the clay model is still the most important tool for a final evaluation of the exterior design of a vehicle and, therefore, is used throughout the industry.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The designer responsible for the vehicles' interior develops the proportions, shape, placement, and surfaces for the instrument panel, seats, door trim panels, headliner, pillar trims, etc.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Here the emphasis is on ergonomics and the comfort of the passengers.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The procedure here is the same as with exterior design (sketch, digital model, and clay model).
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The color and trim (or color and materials) designer is responsible for the research, design, and development of all interior and exterior colors and materials used on a vehicle.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] These include paints, plastics, fabric designs, leather, grains, carpet, headliner, wood trim, and so on.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Color, contrast, texture, and pattern must be carefully combined to give the vehicle a unique interior environment experience.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Designers work closely with exterior and interior designers.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Designers draw inspiration from other design disciplines such as industrial design, fashion, home furnishing, architecture, and sometimes product design.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Specific research is done into global trends to design for projects two to three model years in the future.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Trend boards are created from this research to keep track of design influences as they relate to the automotive industry.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The designer then uses this information to develop themes and concepts that are then further refined and tested on the vehicle models.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The design team also develops graphics for items, such as badges, decals, dials, switches, kick or tread strips, or liveries.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The sketches and rendering are transformed into 3D digital surface modeling and rendering for real-time evaluation with Math data in the initial stages.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] During the development process succeeding phases will require the 3D model fully developed to meet the aesthetic requirements of a designer as well as all engineering and manufacturing requirements.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The fully developed CAS digital model will be re-developed for manufacturing meeting the Class-A surface standards that involve both technical as well as aesthetics.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] A Product Engineering team will further develop this data.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] These modelers usually have a background in industrial design or sometimes tooling engineering in the case of some Class-A modelers.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Autodesk Alias and ICEM Surf are the two most widely used software tools for Class-A development.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Uniform surface continuity is critical to ensure Class-A surface standards.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The continuity of the areas is between the quality grades G0 through G3, with G3 guaranteeing the cleanest patch-to-patch transitions.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The design process occurs concurrently with other product engineers who will be engineering the styling data for meeting performance, manufacturing, and safety regulations.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] From mid-phase, back-and-forth interactions between the designers and product engineers culminate into a finished product being manufacturing-ready.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Apart from this the engineering team parallelly works in the following areas.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Product Engineering (Body In White Sheetmetal Design and Plastic engineering), NVH Development team, Prototype development, Powertrain engineering, Physical Vehicle validation, Tool and Die development, and Manufacturing process design.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The design team for a specific model consists of a chief designer and an exterior as well as an interior designer.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] In some cases, all three roles are done by one designer.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Several junior designers are involved in the development process as well and make specific contributions all overseen by the chief designer.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Apart from this, the color and trim designer works closely with other designers.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The clay model team and digital model team work closely with the styling team all located within the studio.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Apart from this, there would be studio heads, studio managers, and prototype engineers who would work across all teams in the studio.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The total team size for developing a full car usually ranges from 25 to 40 members and the development time lasts for more than 24 months until signed-off for tooling and production.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] After that, a smaller team would be working until the vehicle launch.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] In the early days of the automobile, manufacturers prioritized function over form, focusing on building simple, reliable, and affordable vehicles.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Some automakers began incorporating artists to combine styling with engineering.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Visual appeal remained secondary to technical and safety advancements until the 1930s, an era that, despite its financial challenges, became a high point of creative coachbuilding.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] World War II halted the momentum, but it evolved when the industry restarted in the late 1940s, heavily influenced by the Jet Age.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] However, the artwork and models created by designers are routinely destroyed so as not to be seen by competing automakers.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Great car designers are visionary artists who can translate their ideas from sketches and models into tangible vehicles.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Their work is a blend of artistry and engineering, shaped by collaborations with engineers who help bring their creative concepts to life.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Some automobile forms have served to influence the success and careers of successive designers.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] In the United States, automotive design reached a turning point in the 1920s when the American national automobile market began reaching saturation.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] To maintain unit sales, General Motors head Alfred P.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Sloan Jr. suggested annual model-year design changes to convince car owners that they needed to buy a new replacement each year, an idea borrowed from the bicycle industry (though Sloan usually gets the credit or blame).
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Critics called his strategy planned obsolescence.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Sloan preferred the term "dynamic obsolescence".
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] This strategy had far-reaching effects on the auto business, the field of product design, and eventually the American economy.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The smaller automakers could not maintain the pace and expense of yearly re-styling.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Henry Ford did not like the model-year change because he clung to an engineer's notions of simplicity, the economics of scale, and design integrity.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] GM surpassed Ford's sales in 1931 and became the dominant company in the industry thereafter.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The frequent design changes also made it necessary to use a body-on-frame rather than the lighter but less adaptable monocoque design used by most European automakers.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] In the 1930s, Chrysler's innovations with aerodynamics helped launch the Chrysler Airflow in 1934, which was revolutionary and radical compared to contemporary vehicles.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] However, inadequate consumer acceptance of the advanced appearance of the cars forced a re-design of succeeding models of the Airflow.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] This marketing experience made the entire industry take note of the high risks involved in incorporating major design advancements into their production cars.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] A major influence on American auto styling and marketing was Harley Earl, who is credited with inventing the idea of a concept car, and who brought the tailfin and other aeronautical design references to auto design starting with the rear fenders of the 1948 Cadillac.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Another notable designer was Chrysler group's designer Virgil Exner, who developed the Forward look design in the mid-1950s.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Exner is also credited with using wind tunnel testing to justify incorporating tailfins, thus moving the company away from boxy-looking cars into more aerodynamic and futuristic designs that were influenced by rockets after WWII.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Other influential automotive designers include Raymond Loewy, who was responsible for a number of Studebaker vehicles such as the Avanti, and Gordon Buehrig, who was responsible for the Auburn 851, as well as the Cord 810 and 812.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Starting in the 1960s, Dick Teague, who spent most of his career with American Motors Corporation (AMC), originated the concept of using interchangeable body panels so as to create a wide array of different vehicles using the same stampings, starting with the AMC Cavalier.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Teague was responsible for automotive designs such as the two-seat AMC AMX muscle car, the subcompact Gremlin, the Pacer, and Matador coupe, as well as the original and market segment-creating, Jeep Cherokee.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Additionally during the 1960s, Ford's first-generation Ford Mustang and Thunderbird marked another era leading into new market segments from Detroit.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The Ford Mustang achieved record sales in its first year of production and established the pony car segment.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Personal injury litigation has affected the design and appearance of the car in the 20th century.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Until World War I, most automakers were concerned with mechanical reliability rather than the external appearance of their cars.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Later, luxury and aesthetics became a demand, and also an effective marketing tool.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Designs from each nation with their own strong cultural identity are reflected in their exterior and interior designs.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] World War II slowed the progress, but after the early 1950s, Italian designers set the trend and remained the driving force until the early part of the 1980s.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] In France notable designs came from Bugatti and Avions Voisin.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Of the mass-selling cars, Citroën launched their vehicles with innovative designs and engineering, aided by the styling of Flaminio Bertoni as evident from the Citroën DS.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] After World War II, with the decline of the coachbuilding industry, French automakers (except Citroën) followed British and other popular trends until they gained financial stability.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] During the 1980s, manufacturers like Renault cultivated their own strong design identities with designers like Patrick Le Quément.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Peugeot, which was dependent on Pininfarina since the early post-war period, later established its own brand identity from the 1980s onwards.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Its other company, Citroën, still retains its distinctive French innovations for its designs.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Great Britain was Europe's leading manufacturer of automobiles until the late-1960s.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] During that era, there were more British-based automakers than in the rest of Europe combined.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The British automobile industry catered to all segments ranging from compact, budget, sports, utility, and luxury-type cars.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Car design in Britain was markedly different from other European designs largely because British designers were not influenced by other European art or design movements, as well as the British clay modelers, used a different sweep set.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] British cars until World War II were sold in most of the British colonies.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Innovations in vehicle packaging and chassis engineering combined with global familiarity with British designs meant vehicles were acceptable to public tastes at that time.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] British skilled resources such as panel beaters, die machinists, and clay modelers were also available partly due to their involvement with the motorsport industry.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Still, during the 1960s, British manufacturers sought professional help from Italian designers and studios such as Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, and Pininfarina.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Notable British contributions to automobile designs were the Morris Mini by Alec Issigonis, several Jaguar Cars by Sir William Lyons and Malcolm Sayer, Aston Martin DB Series, and several cars from Triumph and MG.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Ford Europe, based in Great Britain, is notable for the Ford Sierra line, a work of Uwe Bahnsen, Robert Lutz, and Patrick le Quément.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Other notable British designers include William Towns for Aston Martin, and David Bache for Land Rover and Range Rover, and Ian Callum for Jaguar.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] During the complex changes in the British car industry in the 1990s and beyond, a mix of designers worked on all of the remaining mainstream brands under one design director and in one studio.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The director most involved was Geoff Upex, with his team of Richard Woolley, Dave Saddington, George Thomson, Alan Mobberley, and Martin Peach (colour and trim).
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Germany is often considered the birthplace of industrial design with the Bauhaus School of Design, before it was closed down by the Nazi regime.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Ferdinand Porsche and his family played a significant role in German design.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Mercedes-Benz passenger cars were also in the luxury segment and played an important role in German car design.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] After the 1980s, German design evolved into a distinctive Teutonic style often to complement their highly engineered cars suited to Autobahns.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The early German design clues of the present-day owe some part to Italian designers like Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, and Giorgetto Giugiaro.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] During the mid- and late-20th century one of the most influential coach builders/designers in Germany was Karmann.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] German designs started gaining popularity after the 1980s, notable after the formation of Audi.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Volkswagen, which was dependent on Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Karmann, later formed the contemporary design language along with Audi.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] BMW entered the automobile design with sporty-looking everyday sedans using Giovanni Michelotti.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] These models were later enhanced by Ercole Spada into the 1980s, and Klaus Luthe until the mid-1990s.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The American-born designer Chris Bangle was hired by BMW in the late-1990s to redefine the brand.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Bangle incorporated new single-press technology for compound curves to add controversial styling elements to his designs.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The Porsche family contribution was instrumental in the evolution of Porsche cars, while the Italian designer Bruno Sacco helped create various Mercedes Models from the 1960s to the 1990s.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] In Italy, Fiat and Alfa Romeo played a major role in car design.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Many coachbuilders were dependent on these two major manufacturers.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Italian manufacturers had a large presence in motorsports leading to several sport car manufacturers like Ferrari, Lancia, Lamborghini, Maserati, etc.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] During the late-1950s, Italian automobile designs gained global popularity coinciding with the modern fashion and architecture at that time around the world.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Various design and technical schools in Turin turned out designers on a large scale.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] By the late-1960s, almost all Italian coachbuilders transformed into design studios catering to automakers around the world.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The trend continued in the 1990s when the Japanese and Korean manufacturers sourced designs from these styling studios.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Some Italian designers whose design services were sought globally include Aldo Brovarone, Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Walter de Silva.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Sweden had Volvo and Saab as domestic automakers, and the nation's northern location required that cars needed to withstand Nordic climate conditions.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] The Scandinavian design elements are known for their minimalism and simplicity.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] One of the early original Scandinavian designs was the Saab 92001 by Sixten Sason and Gunnar Ljungström.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Koenigsegg, founded in the 1990s, became Sweden's first domestic producer of high end sports cars, with many of their models featuring in house designs by Swedish designers.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Before World War II and until the early-1990s, Czechoslovakia had a strong presence in the automotive industry with manufacturers like Škoda, Jawa, Tatra, CZ, Praga, and Zetor.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] Czech automobiles were generally known for their originality in mechanical simplicity and designs were remarkably Bohemian as evident from Tatra cars and Jawa motorcycles.
[src:dodge-durango/automotive-design] During the Communist regime, the design started falling back and ultimately the domestic automakers ended up as subsidiaries of EU-based companies.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The **Dodge Durango** is a mid-size SUV produced by Dodge starting with the 1998 model year.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The first two generations were very similar in that both were based on the Dodge Dakota and Dodge Ram, both featured a body-on-frame construction and both were produced at the Newark Assembly Plant in Newark, Delaware through the 2009 model year.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The third-generation Durango began with the 2011 model year.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] It is built on the same platform as the Jeep Grand Cherokee, features unibody construction, and has been assembled at the Jefferson North Assembly Plant in Detroit, Michigan, since late 2010.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Each generation had options for different engine sizes and power ratings, with different transmissions also.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] In 2009 a hybrid variant was introduced, but ended quickly with the second generation Durango.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] From 2007 to 2009 the Durango was available as the **Chrysler Aspen** from Chrysler.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Over two million Durangos have been sold since it was introduced in 1998.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The Durango was marketed as a sturdy truck-based SUV designed to hold up to seven passengers and tow up to 7,500 lb (3,400 kg) when properly equipped.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The Durango shared a front end, instrument panel, and front seats with the Dakota pickup on which it was based, and its taillights and liftgate handle with Chrysler's minivan models of the time (the Dodge Caravan, Plymouth Voyager and Chrysler Town & Country).
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Original designs of the eight-passenger Durango featured a rear-facing third-row similar to many older station wagons.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] To make room for a more practical forward-facing third row, Dodge shortened the length of the front doors and raised the roof two inches (5 cm) beyond the front seats, allowing for stadium seating.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The Durango's roof rack was designed to mask the appearance of the raised roof.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The 4.7 L PowerTech V8 replaced the 5.2 L Magnum V8 engine for 2000; however, the 5.2 was still available in the early 2000 models.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] In that same year, a special AWD performance version called the R/T was released with a 5.9 L Magnum V8.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] In 1999 and 2000, a limited-edition Shelby S.P.360 version was offered that featured a supercharged version of the 5.9 L Magnum V8 engine.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Exterior modifications include unique wheels, tires, suspension, and bumpers.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] It came standard with Viper blue paint with two racing stripes down the center of the truck.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] It had a 0 to 60 mph (0 to 97 km/h) time of 7.1 seconds.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] For 1999, the Durango was made available with two-wheel drive.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] A 3.9 L Magnum V6 engine was available, but few were sold.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Minor changes were made for the second year, two new paint colors, and options that included 6-by-9-inch (150 mm × 230 mm) heated rearview mirrors and steering-wheel-mounted radio controls.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Leather seats became standard on SLT Plus models, and body-color wheel flares became standard on SLT Plus and four-wheel drive models.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The 2000 model year included a new 4.7 L Magnum V8 engine, which replaced the reliable 5.2 L Magnum V8, as the standard engine for four-wheel drive models.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The 3.9 L Magnum V6 engine was no longer available, leaving only V8s for the rest of the production run.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The high-performance Durango R/T came equipped with a performance-tuned 5.9 L Magnum V8 and all-wheel drive.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] For 2001, Dodge focused on interior upgrades as Durango's interior trim panels, dash-mounted controls, instrument panel, overhead console, and steering wheel were all redesigned.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The transfer case selector on 4X4 models changed from a manual lever on the console to a switch on the dash.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The instrument cluster was updated, and an electronic vehicle information center was incorporated into the overhead console.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] For improved rear passenger comfort, a dual-zone climate-control system was added as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Sound systems were improved on all models and now came standard with six speakers.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Other minor changes included door panels, revised seats, aluminum wheels, and minor changes to trim options.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] In 2002, the new SXT version of the Durango was offered as the entry-level trim package.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Optional side curtain airbags were added for safety.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The 2003 Durango featured minor mechanical changes, most notable was the addition of four-wheel disc brakes.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] In 1999, the 4WD 5.2 L V8 and the 4WD 5.9 L V8 held the best crash test results, earning a 6.8 out of 10 total rating.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] 360** trim levels included the 5.9 L Magnum V8 engine as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The second-generation Durango was first shown as a concept dubbed Dodge Durango R/T concept at the 2003 Detroit Auto Show.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] It debuted shortly before the companion Dakota.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Like the Dakota, it has much in common with the large Dodge Ram pickup, including a fully boxed frame.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] It is 7 in (180 mm) longer, 2 in (51 mm) wider, and 3 in (76 mm) taller than the previous model.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] It also offered a third-row bench with three seats, giving it an eight-seat capacity.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The design took its styling primarily from the Dodge Powerbox concept, which was itself based on the 1999 Dodge Power Wagon concept, and the 2003–2004 Durango R/T concept.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The steering wheel and gauges are shared with the Dakota (2005–2011), and the steering wheel was only shared with the Ram Pickup (2004–2008).
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Debuting for 2004 was a new coil-spring rear suspension for the solid rear axle.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] A Watt's linkage system is fitted to the rear axle, centering the axle and reducing rear-end skate over rough surfaces, and allowing a lower and wider cargo floor.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] All trim levels offered the 4.7 L Power-Tech V8 engine as standard equipment, though the 5.7 L Hemi V8 engine was available on all trim levels, except for the base **SXT** trim level.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The base **SXT** trim level also offered the 3.7 L Power-Tech V6 engine as standard equipment in place of the 5.7 L Hemi V8 engine option, though the V6 engine option was only available on the base **SXT** trim level, and only between 2004 and 2007.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The 2004 Dodge Durango was the first SUV in DaimlerChrysler's lineup to introduce the 5.7 L Hemi V8 engine, as well as a new radio design and modernized interior features.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The 2007 model year featured a facelift that debuted at the Dallas Auto Show in April 2006.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] It featured a redesigned grille, hood, headlamps, fenders, and wheels.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] New features included electronic stability control, rear park assist, and a one-touch turn signal.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] In 2006, DaimlerChrysler introduced a full-size luxury SUV based on the Durango, called the Chrysler Aspen, for the 2007 model year.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] For 2009, a hybrid variant of the Dodge Durango and its brother, the Chrysler Aspen, was introduced, This system used the GM-designed two-stage hybrid system and added two 87 hp electric motors to the 5.7L V8 with a total system output of around 400 horsepower.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] All Durango and Aspen hybrids came standard with 4-wheel drive.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The whole hybrid setup increased the weight of the car by 400 pounds (180 kg) and cost an additional $4,000 over the standard 5.7L Durango/Aspen.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The fuel economy for the Durango/Aspen hybrid was improved to 19 miles per gallon in the city, and 20 on the highway, increased from the Hemi's 13 city, 18 highway.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] But, two months after the car debuted, Chrysler discontinued the hybrid, citing demand had dropped for their full size SUVs due to economic slowdown.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] They also announced the shutting down of Newark Assembly plant where the hybrid versions were made.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Estimated overall production figures for the Durango and Aspen hybrid is around 800 cars.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The Chrysler Aspen is a luxury SUV from Chrysler.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Launched for the 2007 model year, the Aspen was based on the second generation Durango.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The Aspen was the first truck-based SUV commercialized under the Chrysler brand, although the PT Cruiser was the first truck-based Chrysler brand vehicle as classified under Corporate Average Fuel Economy's (CAFE) regulation.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] With this introduction, as of 2007, all American automobile brands had an SUV in their range.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The Aspen was unveiled at the 2005 North American International Auto Show.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] It came equipped with three rows of seating for eight passengers and available all-wheel drive, and was only available in one single trim, Limited.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The vehicle appears in the 2006 film *Deck the Halls* and game *The Movies: Stunts and Effects* released the same year.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Partly due to slow sales, but mostly because the Chrysler-Dodge-Jeep network of dealers merged, it was discontinued after the 2009 model year.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] However, the Dodge Durango Citadel covers the mid-size luxury SUV segment as of 2011.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] In October 2008, Chrysler announced that the shutdown of the Newark Assembly facility, which produced the Durango and the Chrysler Aspen, would be moved up to the end of 2008, thereby ending production of the Aspen and Durango after the 2009 model year.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] After announcing the discontinuation of the Durango after the 2009 model year, Dodge released an Internet site and teaser photos of the third-generation Dodge Durango on August 16, 2010.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The 2011 Dodge Durango entered production on December 14, 2010, alongside the second-generation Charger in the 2011 vehicle lineup.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] It went on sale for general dealership availability in mid-January 2011.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The third-generation Durango is built alongside the Jeep Grand Cherokee at the Jefferson North Assembly Plant in Detroit, Michigan, sharing the assembly line, running gear, powertrains, and chassis parts with the Grand Cherokee.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] With a slightly longer wheelbase than the Grand Cherokee, the Durango features three rows of seating.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The third-generation Durango features four engines.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The base engine is a new 3.6-liter V6 engine producing 290 hp (216 kW; 294 PS) and 260 lb⋅ft (353 N⋅m; 36 kg⋅m) of torque at 4,800 rpm; 90% of peak torque is available from 1,600 to 6,400 rpm.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The Pentastar V6 engine is backed by a Mercedes W5A580 five-speed automatic, with Chrysler's controls and the driver-interactive control.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Since 2014, Dodge had exclusively used the ZF eight-speed gearbox in two versions in the Durango.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] All V8's have the ZF 8HP, with all V6s using the Chrysler-built 850re version of the ZF 8HP.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The 5.7-liter Hemi VVT V8 returned with 360 hp (268 kW; 365 PS) and 390 lb⋅ft (529 N⋅m; 54 kg⋅m) of torque, which features the 545RFE five-speed automatic.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The Hemi V8 also comes with a "fuel-saver" (cylinder deactivation) mode.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] This feature is primarily used when the vehicle is cruising at constant speeds on level ground.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] In 2021, a supercharged 6.2-liter Hemi V8 was introduced for the SRT Hellcat trim level.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The supercharged 6.2 L Hemi V8 along with the Durango SRT Hellcat trim level was discontinued for the 2022 model year as the engine was unable to be modified further to comply with more stringent automotive emissions requirements.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] However, emissions changes were adopted for the 2023 model year that allowed the SRT Hellcat trim to return.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The 6.4-liter Hemi returned for the 2026 model year in the R/T 392 model.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Dodge unveiled its revised 2014 model Durango at the 2013 New York International Auto Show.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The 2014 Durango was redesigned with sportier-looking lines, an eight-speed automatic transmission, and a new design trim similar to the Rallye, with a blackened plastic bumper and outline.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The taillights were reworked to feature a single LED 'Racetrack' tail lamp similar to the Charger and Dart.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] On the inside, Dodge added a revised steering wheel, instrument cluster, rotary shift knob, and a reconfigurable 20 in (510 mm) thin film transistor display first seen on the Dart.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] For 2016 the Durango received the Pentastar Upgrade V6 which adds Stop/Start, Variable Valve Lift and better engine refinement through a 15% enhanced torque curve and increasing the Variable Valve Timing from 50 degrees to 70 degrees.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Other technologies include Cooled EGR and friction reduction.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Despite the added tech, the engine weighs 4 pounds (1.8 kg) less.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Power output and torque remain the same at 293 horsepower (218 kW; 297 PS) and 260 pound-feet (353 N⋅m; 36 kg⋅m) (single exhaust) or 295 horsepower (220 kW; 299 PS) and 260 pound-feet (353 N⋅m; 36 kg⋅m) torque (dual exhaust).
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The Durango also added new packages to its two trims, with the Anodized Platinum package for the Citadel trim and the Brass Monkey package for the Limited trim.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] For 2017, the Dodge Durango Limited trim was discontinued and replaced by the new GT trim and the Base SXT trim level will now be available with three-row seating fitting seven passengers.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] For 2018, all models received the new Uconnect radios and the second-generation ZF 8-speed automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The rotary transmission gear shifter has been replaced with a T-grip handle like in the Dodge Charger.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The steering wheel has also been changed to a more sporty wheel like found in the Dodge Charger.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Other changes include suede insert leather seats and black chrome inserts in the interior on the GT model.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] For 2019: The Tow Group IV package gets an integrated trailer brake controller.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The Dodge Durango GT trim gets the R/T- and SRT-style grille.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] A new GT Plus trim is added which adds several amenities to the GT trim, such as heated front and second-row seats and steering wheel; 6-way passenger power seat with 4-way lumbar adjustment; two-position memory for the driver's seat, radio, and mirrors; a power liftgate; and 150W inverter.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] For 2021, the Durango receives updated exterior styling, with a revised bumper and headlights, three grille textures, and six new wheel designs.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The interior features a new instrument panel with Uconnect 5; an 8.4-inch screen is standard on SXT and GT models, while R/T and Citadel models have a 10.1-inch touchscreen.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] An SRT Hellcat model with a 710 hp supercharged 6.2 L Hemi V8 was available for 2021 only, after which it was discontinued due to emissions requirements.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] With the discontinuation of the smaller Journey, the Durango becomes the only SUV in the Dodge vehicle lineup as of 2021.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] In 2023, the Dodge Hornet was introduced making the Durango the largest vehicle in the Dodge lineup.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] For 2023, Dodge restructured the entire Durango lineup, dividing each individual model into three different trim levels: "Base" (without an additional trim level designation), "Plus", and "Premium" (the latter available on GT models and above).
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] Due to the restructuring of the trim lineup, there are now fewer available options and package on each model, as the previously-available options and packages are now consolidated into the three trim levels.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The SXT Plus now carries a lower Manufacturer's Suggested Retail Price (MSRP) than the base SXT, starting $450 less at $40,140 versus $40,590.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] SXT, SXT Plus, and GT are now the only trims of the Durango lineup to feature the standard U Connect 5 8.4 infotainment system, as all other trims now feature the upgraded U Connect 5 10.1 infotainment system as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] On August 16, 2012, Chrysler recalled 1,661 2013-model Dodge Durango sport utility vehicles in the United States and Canada because some airbags may not deploy in an accident.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The recall affects 1,449 of the seven-passenger versions of the SUVs in the United States and 212 in Canada and other markets.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] On July 24, 2015, Chrysler recalled all 2014-2015 Dodge Durangos with the 8.4-inch (210 mm) touch-screens due to security concerns with the software that controls the vehicle because it could be hacked.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The vulnerability was discovered by software engineers Charlie Miller and Chris Valasek and initially posted on *Wired*.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] This vulnerability would allow hackers to remotely access and take over a variety of features, including those key parts of driving via a vulnerability in the Uconnect infotainment system.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] On November 26, 2019, Chrysler issued a recall of 700,000 2011-2013 Durangos and Jeep Grand Cherokees in the United States, Canada, and Mexico, because of an electrical failure that can cause the engine not to start or stop functioning while it is driving.
[src:dodge-durango/dodge-durango] The FCA group announced a free revision to both models and replacement of these pieces involved in the problem.
